00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:06.440
One of the exciting things for me about
Rauschenberg is that he was relentlessly

00:00:06.440 --> 00:00:13.530
collaborative, so if you look at the
exhibition there are collaborations with

00:00:13.530 --> 00:00:21.689
scientists, with artists, with writers,
with dancers, with musicians. He imagines

00:00:21.689 --> 00:00:26.849
that there is a universe of
interconnected disciplines and

00:00:26.849 --> 00:00:31.529
interconnected thought. He's in the
middle of this you know to himself he

00:00:31.529 --> 00:00:36.570
imagines there's all this exciting stuff
happening in the world and if I put

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:41.629
myself there I can be right at the
center of it.

00:00:48.289 --> 00:00:54.090
Classical music is very small and it's
very local and  it lives in a little tiny

00:00:54.090 --> 00:00:59.789
box and so for me one of the really
exciting things is that when I see

00:00:59.789 --> 00:01:05.760
someone who was able to define the world
as on being all these incredible

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:10.770
connections that only connect because
they connect in him, it makes me feel

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:15.180
like I can do that. It makes me feel like
I can live a bigger life. And it makes me

00:01:15.180 --> 00:01:20.880
feel like the music which I believe
fundamentally is universal—that the

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:25.000
music can be part of a larger kind of
citizenship.

00:01:31.370 --> 00:01:37.970
The New York School is a historic term.
It means a moment in time in the 1950s

00:01:37.970 --> 00:01:44.970
when composers started looking at ways
to challenge ideas that came from Europe

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:53.240
by incorporating freedom and
indeterminacy and democracy and music

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:05.120
And thank you all for coming and for
those of you who haven't seen the show

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:13.720
yet you should rush to see it. It's
incredible, and this piece, in particular, 4 Minutes and 33...

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:17.840
The central figure
in this New York School was always John Cage.

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:25.160
One of Cage's most notorious pieces
is a piece called Four Minutes and 33 Seconds.

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:45.500
Cage saw the white paintings of
Rauschenberg and realized how powerful

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:54.100
the provocation was to have something on
which you could project anything.

00:02:54.100 --> 00:03:02.860
So it was given to David Tudor who at the time
was the avant-garde music world's

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:08.280
greatest virtuoso of the most difficult
piano music.

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:13.260
The idea that you are asking this incredible virtuoso

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:17.200
to sit down at the piano, we expect him to do something.

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:22.720
So what he does is he takes out the
music and he closes the lid of the piano

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:27.790
for the time specified for this first
movement, and he opens the lid of the

00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:31.840
piano and he closes the lid of the piano
for the second movement, and he does this

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:34.980
for all three movements for four minutes
and 33 seconds.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:36.900
He really is the closest

00:03:36.910 --> 00:03:43.680
thing that music composition has to a
philosopher. It's Cage identifying what

00:03:43.690 --> 00:03:50.740
the core action of composition is.
Composition is the designing of an

00:03:50.740 --> 00:03:56.980
experience which makes an audience a
better listener. Something happens in

00:03:56.980 --> 00:04:02.530
sound in front of you and you put it
together and you listen to it. If there's

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:06.760
an emotional reaction that's not that's
happening, it's not that the composer

00:04:06.760 --> 00:04:11.700
makes you have the emotional reaction—
you are making that emotional reaction

00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:17.860
yourself. How better to show that that's
the core of what classical music is than

00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:25.160
to say there is nothing on stage other
than the opening of the proposition to listen.

