00:05:08.060 --> 00:05:12.620
There was a moment where David Tudor moved
from being a performer, a recreator

00:05:12.620 --> 00:05:17.599
into being a creator and that was
something that Rauschenberg did for

00:05:17.599 --> 00:05:25.729
David Tudor. Rauschenberg invited David
Tudor to participate in a project with

00:05:25.729 --> 00:05:32.900
him and David Tudor's idea was he walked
into this gigantic hall where there were

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:38.479
two hundred and seventy plus fluorescent
lights in the ceiling and he put a

00:05:38.479 --> 00:05:43.669
microphone on every single one of the
lights and so then he had a little

00:05:43.669 --> 00:05:49.540
control board where he would make music
by turning the lights on and off

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:54.520
So one of the things that we've done for our
show here is that we've made a kind of

00:05:54.529 --> 00:05:58.460
homage to this piece. You don't want to
dim it? Because that's sometimes where

00:05:58.460 --> 00:06:04.170
you get the fun flicker
there's a problem with the fact that

00:06:04.170 --> 00:06:08.260
contemporary fluorescent lights don't
make sound for the most part. They're

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:11.770
lighting modern lighting fixtures are
very very quiet, and so I had to go and

00:06:11.770 --> 00:06:16.930
find some recordings of vintage
fluorescent tubes and utilize those in a

00:06:16.930 --> 00:06:21.100
sort of software environment that allows
us to turn on and off fluorescent lights

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:26.050
in a way that corresponds with sounds
that would be, you know, as near as we can

00:06:26.050 --> 00:06:30.780
tell would be appropriate to what we
might have heard in that gallery space

00:06:50.330 --> 00:06:57.150
Rauschenberg saw that there shouldn't be
a distance between composer and

00:06:57.150 --> 00:07:01.920
performer, just as he saw that there
shouldn't be a distance between artist

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:09.930
and choreographer or artist and costumer
or composer and poet. He imagined that

00:07:09.930 --> 00:07:18.120
somebody could do this job, and that kind
of enthusiasm and an invitation ended up

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:26.580
changing David Tudor's life. The notion
that you should be making your work and

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:31.860
also living in a world and giving
opportunities to other people and

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:36.720
helping people grow and finding people
who are interesting, who are interesting

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:42.690
and supporting them—that's rare. The
idea that he can be useful to someone

00:07:42.690 --> 00:07:45.800
else,
that is very beautiful and that goes...

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:48.700
that's a theme that goes through this
entire show.

